  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering. These establish frameworks for countries to cooperate and implement their own domestic laws to prevent, detect, and prosecute money laundering.  Here are some of the key ones:\n\n*   **The Financial Action Task Force (FATF):** While not a treaty or convention, FATF is the primary international standard-setting body for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and proliferation financing. It develops the **FATF Recommendations**, which are internationally recognized standards that countries are expected to implement. FATF also assesses countries' compliance with these standards and identifies jurisdictions with weak AML/CFT (Anti-Money Laundering/Counter-Terrorist Financing) regimes.\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988):** This convention was one of the first international agreements to address money laundering. It requires countries to criminalize the laundering of proceeds from drug trafficking and to cooperate in international investigations.\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000):** This convention expands on the 1988 convention by requiring countries to criminalize the laundering of proceeds from a wider range of crimes, not just drug trafficking.\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Corruption (2003):** This convention focuses on preventing and combating corruption, including the laundering of proceeds from corruption.\n*   **Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime (1990) and revised in 2005:** This convention, and its updated version, aim to facilitate international cooperation in investigating and prosecuting money laundering offenses and confiscating illicit proceeds. It is primarily a regional agreement for Council of Europe member states, but is open to other countries as well.\n\n**Key Aspects of International AML Efforts:**\n\n*   **Criminalization of Money Laundering:** Requires countries to make money laundering a crime under their domestic laws.\n*   **Customer Due Diligence (CDD):** Requires financial institutions to identify and verify the identities of their customers.\n*   **Record Keeping:** Requires financial institutions to maintain records of transactions for a certain period of time.\n*   **Suspicious Activity Reporting (SAR):** Requires financial institutions to report suspicious transactions to law enforcement.\n*   **International Cooperation:** Requires countries to cooperate with each other in investigating and prosecuting money laundering offenses.\n*   **Asset Forfeiture:** Allows for the seizure and forfeiture of assets derived from illegal activities.\n\n**In summary:**  A network of international laws, conventions, and standards exists to fight money laundering. These instruments encourage countries to implement their own laws and work together to detect, prevent, and prosecute money laundering activities across borders. The FATF Recommendations are a crucial component, serving as a global benchmark for effective AML/CFT regimes.\n",
